WEBVTT

1
00:00:37.327 --> 00:00:41.331
<i>The first atomic bomb
heralded the dawn of a troubling new era.</i>


2
00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:46.836
<i>In a single stroke, the Japanese city
of Hiroshima and some 70,000 men,</i>


3
00:00:46.920 --> 00:00:49.047
<i>women, and children were annihilated.</i>

4
00:00:50.131 --> 00:00:53.760
<i>In the years since, that momentous event
has come under increasing scrutiny.</i>


5
00:00:56.763 --> 00:00:59.891
<i>Was the bomb
a price worth paying for pea...</i>


6
00:01:16.699 --> 00:01:20.870
<i>The physicists who participated
in forging the most formidable</i>


7
00:01:20.954 --> 00:01:23.540
<i>and dangerous weapon of all time</i>

8
00:01:23.623 --> 00:01:27.627
<i>are harassed
by an equal feeling of responsibility,</i>


9
00:01:28.253 --> 00:01:29.546
<i>not to say guilt.</i>

10
00:01:35.009 --> 00:01:39.055
<i>Dr. Albert Einstein,
one of the world's greatest scientists.</i>


11
00:01:39.556 --> 00:01:44.185
<i>A scientific giant who sometimes
generated political controversy,</i>


12
00:01:44.269 --> 00:01:45.854
<i>as well as brilliant equations.</i>

13
00:01:46.437 --> 00:01:48.481
<i>Called the father of the atomic age,</i>

14
00:01:48.565 --> 00:01:50.733
<i>Einstein's great contribution
to human knowledge</i>


15
00:01:50.817 --> 00:01:53.111
<i>was his theory of relativity.</i>

16
00:01:53.194 --> 00:01:56.698
<i>The key to the atom secrets was
first given to the world when the genius,</i>


17
00:01:56.781 --> 00:02:00.368
<i>Albert Einstein, defined the relation
between all matter and energy.</i>


18
00:02:01.411 --> 00:02:04.706
<i>E is equal to MC squared.</i>

19
00:02:05.582 --> 00:02:07.041
<i>Had I known</i>

20
00:02:07.125 --> 00:02:10.795
<i>that the Germans would not succeed
in producing an atomic bomb,</i>


21
00:02:12.130 --> 00:02:16.509
<i>I would not have taken part
in opening that Pandora's box.</i>


22
00:02:36.738 --> 00:02:39.365
Hail to victory!

23
00:03:25.954 --> 00:03:29.499
<i>Order! Motion under the ten-minute rule,</i>

24
00:03:29.582 --> 00:03:33.586
<i>bill to promote and extend
opportunities of citizenship for Jews</i>


25
00:03:33.670 --> 00:03:36.130
<i>resident outside the British Empire.</i>

26
00:03:36.214 --> 00:03:39.759
<i>- Commander Locker-Lampson.
- Thank you, Mr. Speaker.</i>


27
00:03:41.135 --> 00:03:44.180
<i>I am not personally a Jew,</i>

28
00:03:44.973 --> 00:03:48.518
<i>but I hope
that I do not require to be a Jew</i>


29
00:03:49.269 --> 00:03:52.021
<i>to hate tyranny anywhere in the world.</i>

30
00:03:53.398 --> 00:03:56.818
<i>Germany has selected
the cream of her culture</i>


31
00:03:56.901 --> 00:03:58.695
<i>and suppressed it.</i>

32
00:04:00.697 --> 00:04:03.491
<i>She has even turned upon
her most glorious citizen.</i>


33
00:04:03.992 --> 00:04:05.076
<i>Einstein.</i>

34
00:04:07.954 --> 00:04:12.292
<i>The road hog and racketeer of Europe
have plundered his place.</i>


35
00:04:12.375 --> 00:04:14.210
<i>They've even taken away his violin.</i>

36
00:04:17.088 --> 00:04:19.090
<i>Today, Einstein is without a home.</i>

37
00:04:19.757 --> 00:04:22.510
<i>He had to write his name
in a visitor's book in England.</i>


38
00:04:24.470 --> 00:04:27.140
<i>And when he came to write his address,
he put...</i>


39
00:04:28.182 --> 00:04:29.267
<i>"Without any."</i>

40
00:04:40.570 --> 00:04:41.946
Here we are, Professor.

41
00:04:43.114 --> 00:04:44.824
Welcome to Roughton Heath.

42
00:04:45.950 --> 00:04:47.076
Isn't it wonderful?

43
00:04:49.412 --> 00:04:50.955
Let's get you settled in, eh?

44
00:05:11.601 --> 00:05:13.936
I know it's rudimentary
for a man of your importance


45
00:05:14.020 --> 00:05:16.773
but, under your current circumstances...

46
00:05:16.856 --> 00:05:20.276
I believe that a simple
and unassuming life


47
00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:23.154
is best for body and mind.

48
00:05:23.237 --> 00:05:24.447
Couldn't agree more.

49
00:05:25.490 --> 00:05:27.658
What I like best is
a tent on a heath,

50
00:05:28.159 --> 00:05:31.371
plain viands, a glass of beer,

51
00:05:32.038 --> 00:05:35.833
and the sweet communion of... friends.

52
00:05:40.421 --> 00:05:41.714
For you.

53
00:05:44.300 --> 00:05:46.552
To replace the one
the Hun stole from you.

54
00:05:49.138 --> 00:05:50.807
I'll let you unpack in peace.

55
00:06:04.987 --> 00:06:07.532
<i>The present state of affairs in Germany</i>

56
00:06:07.615 --> 00:06:11.119
<i>is a state of psychic distemper
in the masses.</i>


57
00:06:13.538 --> 00:06:17.333
<i>Hitler picked up human flotsam
on the streets and in the taverns</i>


58
00:06:17.917 --> 00:06:20.211
<i>and organized them around himself.</i>

59
00:06:21.629 --> 00:06:24.340
<i>The worst outcrop of herd life,</i>

60
00:06:24.424 --> 00:06:27.218
<i>the military system, which I abhor.</i>

61
00:06:31.055 --> 00:06:34.434
<i>German fascism
has been particularly violent</i>


62
00:06:34.517 --> 00:06:37.270
<i>in its attack upon my Jewish brothers.</i>

63
00:06:37.854 --> 00:06:38.938
BE CAREFUL. JEWS.

64
00:06:39.021 --> 00:06:40.356
I AM THE BIGGEST PIG IN TOWN

65
00:06:44.610 --> 00:06:48.489
<i>Our friends in Germany
need not do anything to protect me.</i>


66
00:06:50.199 --> 00:06:54.162
<i>In fact, such action
would needlessly endanger them.</i>


67
00:07:01.669 --> 00:07:06.174
<i>I cannot tell you yet,
whether I shall make England my home.</i>


68
00:07:07.091 --> 00:07:08.091
How is he?

69
00:07:10.470 --> 00:07:11.471
As you'd imagine.

70
00:07:11.971 --> 00:07:15.016
Poor fellow's lost everything,
his home, his money.


71
00:07:15.725 --> 00:07:19.312
And now, I hear the Nazis have placed
a price of 20,000 marks on his head.


72
00:07:19.395 --> 00:07:23.191
I really had no idea
that my head was worth all that.


73
00:07:25.318 --> 00:07:26.861
I assure you, Professor.

74
00:07:27.361 --> 00:07:30.490
You're perfectly safe
from the long arm of fascism here.


75
00:07:32.783 --> 00:07:35.661
Uh, may I introduce Barbara Goodall.

76
00:07:36.662 --> 00:07:37.663
Hello, Professor.

77
00:07:37.747 --> 00:07:39.248
And Margery Howard.

78
00:07:39.332 --> 00:07:40.374
Hello, Professor.

79
00:07:41.209 --> 00:07:42.126
Delighted.

80
00:07:42.210 --> 00:07:44.378
These ladies are your bodyguards.

81
00:07:45.379 --> 00:07:49.675
If any unauthorized person comes near,
believe me, Professor...


82
00:07:49.759 --> 00:07:53.095
They will most certainly get
a charge or two of buckshot.


83
00:07:54.138 --> 00:07:56.682
Sorry, Professor,
I know you're not one for bearing arms,


84
00:07:56.766 --> 00:07:58.726
but really we can't be too careful.

85
00:07:59.852 --> 00:08:01.062
Hope you understand?

86
00:08:03.439 --> 00:08:04.941
Marvelous.

87
00:08:06.150 --> 00:08:08.819
Keep a close eye out, ladies.
I'm relying on you both.


88
00:08:22.375 --> 00:08:26.254
<i>A precious possession
in this world, however,</i>


89
00:08:26.337 --> 00:08:28.339
is one's own people

90
00:08:30.174 --> 00:08:34.303
<i>and we want to lead</i>

91
00:08:34.887 --> 00:08:37.431
<i>and fight for these people.</i>

92
00:08:37.932 --> 00:08:43.980
And never flag, never tire, never despair.

93
00:08:44.063 --> 00:08:46.983
<i>As long as I have
any choice in the matter...</i>


94
00:08:47.984 --> 00:08:51.195
<i>...I shall live only in a country
where civil liberty,</i>


95
00:08:51.279 --> 00:08:55.658
<i>tolerance, and equality
of all citizens before the law prevail.</i>


96
00:08:59.620 --> 00:09:04.000
<i>These conditions do not exist
in Germany at the present time.</i>


97
00:09:05.334 --> 00:09:09.922
<i>This breeding ground of disease
will soon pose a grave danger</i>


98
00:09:10.006 --> 00:09:11.799
<i>for the rest of the world.</i>

99
00:09:11.882 --> 00:09:13.884
We have one aim,

100
00:09:13.968 --> 00:09:19.265
and we will follow it fanatically
and ruthlessly to the grave.


101
00:09:19.348 --> 00:09:21.809
Hail to victory!

102
00:09:23.185 --> 00:09:24.785
<i>To stay in Germany</i>

103
00:09:24.854 --> 00:09:27.690
<i>would have been impossible for me
as a pacifist.</i>


104
00:09:30.401 --> 00:09:33.946
<i>I'm not only a pacifist,
but a militant pacifist.</i>


105
00:09:35.906 --> 00:09:38.200
<i>I am willing to fight for peace.</i>

106
00:09:42.413 --> 00:09:45.207
My great friend has invited me here.

107
00:09:46.208 --> 00:09:49.754
I can live quietly,
working out my mathematical problems.


108
00:09:51.422 --> 00:09:53.049
All I want is peace,

109
00:09:53.549 --> 00:09:56.802
and could I have found
a more peaceful retreat


110
00:09:56.886 --> 00:09:58.596
than here in England?

111
00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:01.390
No one will know where I am.

112
00:10:01.891 --> 00:10:03.601
Indeed not!

113
00:10:04.185 --> 00:10:05.478
Shall we get some pictures?

114
00:10:18.616 --> 00:10:22.411
The Observer <i>diary,

115
00:10:24.163 --> 00:10:26.791
<i>England is not
a very good place to hide in.</i>


116
00:10:27.792 --> 00:10:31.379
<i>Dr. Einstein, who has come here
to escape Nazi persecution,</i>


117
00:10:31.462 --> 00:10:34.507
<i>finds his wooden hut
photographed in the papers</i>


118
00:10:35.299 --> 00:10:37.343
<i>with full indications of locality,</i>

119
00:10:37.843 --> 00:10:41.764
<i>and Cromer Council considers
the question of presenting an address.</i>


120
00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:46.852
<i>Germany, I suppose,
is presumed to be looking the other way.</i>


121
00:10:53.818 --> 00:10:58.531
When did you start thinking about time
and space and all those things, Professor?


122
00:11:07.081 --> 00:11:08.081
Ah!

123
00:11:09.959 --> 00:11:13.045
As a child of four or five,

124
00:11:13.129 --> 00:11:17.800
my father showed me a compass.

125
00:11:19.051 --> 00:11:22.680
This experience made
a deep and lasting impression on me.


126
00:11:23.973 --> 00:11:28.811
That this needle behaved
in such a determined way.


127
00:11:30.271 --> 00:11:33.190
Something deeply hidden
had to be behind things.


128
00:11:35.609 --> 00:11:37.027
When I was four or five,

129
00:11:37.528 --> 00:11:39.572
I couldn't tie my own shoelaces.

130
00:11:42.992 --> 00:11:45.494
The most beautiful thing we can experience

131
00:11:46.829 --> 00:11:47.913
is the mysterious.

132
00:11:58.966 --> 00:12:03.387
<i>I can still remember
my first childish experiments in thinking</i>


133
00:12:03.471 --> 00:12:07.391
<i>that had a direct bearing
on the theory of relativity.</i>


134
00:12:10.060 --> 00:12:13.606
<i>What if one were to run
after a ray of light?</i>


135
00:12:17.234 --> 00:12:19.653
<i>If one were to run fast enough,</i>

136
00:12:19.737 --> 00:12:22.323
<i>would it no longer move at all?</i>

137
00:12:41.300 --> 00:12:44.386
Of course, such a thing is impossible.

138
00:12:45.346 --> 00:12:47.848
Your teachers must have loved you.

139
00:12:48.516 --> 00:12:51.310
"You'll never amount to anything,
Einstein."


140
00:12:51.393 --> 00:12:55.314
"You're an extremely clever boy,
but you have one great fault."


141
00:12:55.397 --> 00:12:57.650
"You'll never let yourself
be told anything."


142
00:12:57.733 --> 00:13:01.445
"Your mere presence spoils
the respect in the class for me."


143
00:13:02.530 --> 00:13:05.991
The teachers had
the characters of drill sergeants.


144
00:13:07.076 --> 00:13:10.204
Mistrust of every kind of authority grew.

145
00:13:11.664 --> 00:13:14.041
An attitude that has never again left me.

146
00:13:21.674 --> 00:13:23.425
<i>It is only men who are free,</i>

147
00:13:25.094 --> 00:13:28.305
<i>who create the inventions
and intellectual works,</i>


148
00:13:28.389 --> 00:13:30.182
<i>which make life worthwhile.</i>

149
00:13:32.893 --> 00:13:35.813
<i>Out yonder there was this huge world,</i>

150
00:13:35.896 --> 00:13:39.316
<i>which stands before us
like a great, eternal riddle.</i>


151
00:13:46.407 --> 00:13:50.119
<i>I became convinced
that nature could be understood</i>


152
00:13:50.202 --> 00:13:53.330
<i>as a relatively simple
mathematical structure.</i>


153
00:13:56.500 --> 00:13:58.878
<i>A storm broke loose in my mind.</i>

154
00:14:02.256 --> 00:14:04.633
<i>Einstein's great theory of relativity.</i>

155
00:14:05.134 --> 00:14:07.970
<i>Two towers flash signals at the same time</i>

156
00:14:08.053 --> 00:14:10.222
<i>to a balloonist
and to a man on the ground.</i>


157
00:14:11.223 --> 00:14:15.227
<i>The observer on the ground says
the signals were given from both towers</i>


158
00:14:15.311 --> 00:14:16.770
<i>at the same time.</i>

159
00:14:19.231 --> 00:14:22.026
<i>Light rays from both towers
are the same length.</i>


160
00:14:24.486 --> 00:14:29.283
<i>But the motion of the balloonist means
one signal takes more time to reach him</i>


161
00:14:29.366 --> 00:14:32.786
<i>and he insists that one tower signaled
before the other.</i>


162
00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:39.251
<i>My solution actually had to do
with the concept of time.</i>


163
00:14:40.544 --> 00:14:43.297
<i>Two observers moving at different speeds</i>

164
00:14:43.380 --> 00:14:47.217
<i>experience time at different rates.</i>

165
00:14:48.969 --> 00:14:52.056
<i>Time cannot be absolutely defined.</i>

166
00:14:54.934 --> 00:14:59.104
<i>Time is relative.
It stretches and shrinks.</i>


167
00:14:59.605 --> 00:15:02.274
<i>Or, in our Earth
language, an hour for us</i>

168
00:15:02.358 --> 00:15:05.527
<i>may be a century on another planet,</i>

169
00:15:05.611 --> 00:15:07.196
<i>and vice versa.</i>

170
00:15:10.449 --> 00:15:14.495
<i>There is no audible ticktock
everywhere in the world.</i>


171
00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:24.964
Past, present, and future
is only an illusion.


172
00:15:26.215 --> 00:15:29.301
But one more consequence
also occurred to me.


173
00:15:30.094 --> 00:15:32.596
According to the theory of relativity,

174
00:15:33.305 --> 00:15:38.310
there is no essential distinction
between mass and energy.


175
00:15:41.021 --> 00:15:45.150
Energy is put equal to mass

176
00:15:46.026 --> 00:15:50.280
multiplied by
the square of the velocity of light.


177
00:15:50.990 --> 00:15:53.867
So, a very small amount of mass

178
00:15:54.410 --> 00:15:58.455
may be converted
into a very large amount of energy.


179
00:16:12.803 --> 00:16:16.432
<i>Kind fate allowed me
to find a couple of nice ideas</i>


180
00:16:16.515 --> 00:16:18.767
<i>after years of feverish labor.</i>

181
00:16:19.268 --> 00:16:20.310
Mr. Einstein.

182
00:16:25.524 --> 00:16:28.861
Einstein! Einstein! Einstein!

183
00:16:38.037 --> 00:16:39.830
Professor Einstein.
Professor.


184
00:16:39.913 --> 00:16:41.665
Professor.

185
00:16:41.749 --> 00:16:42.875
Professor Einstein.

186
00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:44.500
<i>Times of London.</i>

187
00:16:44.543 --> 00:16:47.463
Um, you have caused a revolution
in science,


188
00:16:47.546 --> 00:16:50.174
and Newtonian ideas are overthrown.

189
00:16:50.257 --> 00:16:52.384
<i>New York Times.</i> Our headline today,

190
00:16:52.468 --> 00:16:54.428
"Lights all askew in the heavens!"

191
00:16:54.511 --> 00:16:56.346
"Men of science more or less agog!"

192
00:16:56.430 --> 00:16:59.016
"Einstein's theory triumphs!"
How do you feel?


193
00:16:59.516 --> 00:17:02.102
My faculties have been quite overrated.

194
00:17:03.103 --> 00:17:07.024
Professor, could you possibly
explain your theory to the man<i>,</i>


195
00:17:07.107 --> 00:17:09.401
or possibly the woman, in the street?

196
00:17:10.235 --> 00:17:14.740
An hour sitting with a pretty girl
on a park bench passes like a minute,


197
00:17:14.823 --> 00:17:18.494
but a minute sitting on a hot stove
seems like an hour.


198
00:17:18.577 --> 00:17:19.953
That's relativity.

199
00:17:21.580 --> 00:17:23.415
Very funny. Very funny indeed.

200
00:17:29.421 --> 00:17:33.634
<i>Like the man in the fairy tale
who turned everything into gold,</i>


201
00:17:35.677 --> 00:17:36.929
<i>so with me,</i>

202
00:17:37.012 --> 00:17:40.641
<i>everything is turned
into newspaper clamor.</i>


203
00:17:57.199 --> 00:17:59.993
<i>To punish me for my contempt of authority,</i>

204
00:18:00.994 --> 00:18:03.872
<i>fate made me an authority myself.</i>

205
00:18:11.296 --> 00:18:13.465
It turned out that
the inertia of a system

206
00:18:13.549 --> 00:18:16.718
necessarily depends on its energy content,

207
00:18:16.802 --> 00:18:21.890
and this led straight to the notion
that inert mass is simply latent energy.


208
00:18:24.726 --> 00:18:28.689
Mass and energy are both different
manifestations of the same thing.


209
00:18:28.772 --> 00:18:31.233
So, a small amount of mass

210
00:18:31.316 --> 00:18:34.444
may be converted
into a very large amount of energy.


211
00:18:36.488 --> 00:18:40.659
Sorry, Professor,
but are you saying it could be possible


212
00:18:40.742 --> 00:18:43.036
to, well, somehow release that energy?

213
00:18:43.537 --> 00:18:48.625
Science in its present state
makes it appear almost impossible


214
00:18:48.709 --> 00:18:50.836
that we should ever succeed in so doing.

215
00:18:50.919 --> 00:18:54.756
It would be like, uh,
shooting birds in the dark


216
00:18:54.840 --> 00:18:57.509
in a country
where there are very few birds.


217
00:18:57.593 --> 00:19:02.389
Still, energy released on that scale
sounds... rather worrying.


218
00:19:03.098 --> 00:19:07.769
Concern for man himself and his fate
must always be the chief objective,


219
00:19:08.437 --> 00:19:11.148
in order that the creations of our minds

220
00:19:11.231 --> 00:19:14.026
should be a blessing
and not a curse to mankind.


221
00:19:19.531 --> 00:19:21.241
Stand down, ladies!

222
00:19:22.159 --> 00:19:25.037
I'm expecting someone. 
Friend, not foe.

223
00:19:28.248 --> 00:19:31.168
I think you'll very much enjoy meeting
this gentleman, Professor.


224
00:19:41.011 --> 00:19:43.639
Been spending some more time
chatting with the professor, Margery?


225
00:19:43.722 --> 00:19:47.267
Oh, listening mainly.

226
00:19:47.351 --> 00:19:50.604
He's been explaining the finer points
of his theory of relativity to us.


227
00:19:51.188 --> 00:19:52.188
And?

228
00:19:52.648 --> 00:19:54.858
And I'm quite certain
that he understands it.


229
00:20:07.412 --> 00:20:08.412
Epstein.

230
00:20:08.914 --> 00:20:10.999
No, no. Einstein.

231
00:20:12.876 --> 00:20:15.587
Professor, this is Jacob Epstein.
